  <section class="faq-section"><div class="container">
    <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">FAQs</span><h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Small Cap Funds</h2></div>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Are small cap funds suitable for beginners?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Small cap funds are generally not recommended as a first equity investment due to their high volatility. Beginners should start with large cap or flexi cap funds. Once you've experienced at least one market correction (and stayed invested through it), you can add a small allocation (10%–15%) to small cap funds for enhanced growth potential.</p></div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>How much can small cap funds fall during a market crash?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>During severe corrections, small cap funds can fall 40%–55% from peak to trough. In the 2020 COVID crash, the Nifty Smallcap 250 fell about 45% in just one month. In 2018, small caps fell 40% over 9 months. However, every major small cap crash has been followed by a strong recovery — the 2020 crash was followed by a 150%+ rally over the next 2 years.</p></div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Should I stop my small cap SIP during a market fall?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Absolutely not. Market falls are when SIPs work best — you're buying more units at lower prices. Stopping SIPs during crashes and restarting during rallies is the worst possible strategy. In fact, increasing your SIP amount during corrections (if you have surplus funds) can dramatically boost your long-term returns.</p></div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>What is the exit load on small cap funds?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Most small cap funds charge a 1% exit load if redeemed within 1 year of investment. Each SIP installment is treated separately, so the 1-year period applies to each individual installment. After 1 year, there is no exit load. This exit load structure discourages premature withdrawals and encourages long-term holding.</p></div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Why do some small cap funds restrict new investments?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>When a small cap fund's AUM grows very large (₹20,000+ crore), it becomes difficult for the fund manager to invest in truly small companies without significantly impacting stock prices. To protect existing investors' interests, some funds temporarily restrict new lump sum investments or cap SIP amounts. This is actually a positive sign of responsible fund management.</p></div></div></div>
    </div>
  </div></section>

